T*
(boot, UEFI PXE boot, and UEFI HTTP boot . All of them start by the machine asking a DHCP server) Tj
T*
(for what it should boot, and all of them require different answers from the DHCP server. If you) Tj
T*
(want to support more than one network booting option, your DHCP server needs to give each sort) Tj
T*
(of client the right answer for it, which generally means you have to tell the DHCP server how) Tj
T*
(to tell the types of clients apart. \(If you have all modern machines you can probably get away) Tj
T*
(with only supporting UEFI PXE booting, which will simplify your life slightly.\) The DHCP server) Tj
T*
(we use is the standard and now old-fashioned ISC DHCP server. There are a variety of guides for) Tj
T*
(how to configure your ISC DHCP server for multiple types of network booting, but for various) Tj
